Pandas is a Python library for data analysis and manipulation.

Series is a one-dimensional labeled array (like a single column).

DataFrame is a two-dimensional table of data with rows and columns.

read_csv() loads data from a CSV file into a DataFrame.

head() shows the first few rows of a DataFrame.

tail() shows the last few rows of a DataFrame.

info() gives a summary of the DataFrame's structure.

describe() provides statistical summaries of numeric columns.

df['column'] accesses a single column from the DataFrame.

df.loc[row_index] accesses rows by index label.

df.iloc[row_number] accesses rows by integer position.

Filtering uses conditions to select specific rows (e.g., df[df['Age'] > 18]).

Sorting arranges data using sort_values() by column(s).

GroupBy lets you group data and apply functions like sum, mean, etc.

isnull() checks for missing (NaN) values.

fillna() replaces missing values with a specified value.

dropna() removes rows or columns with missing data.

merge() combines DataFrames based on common columns (like SQL JOIN).

concat() stacks multiple DataFrames vertically or horizontally.

to_csv() exports a DataFrame to a CSV file.
